Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in synthesizing multi-domain dialogues lies not only in generating semantically coherent and contextually accurate utterances but also in ensuring that rewritten turns maintain fidelity to the original user intent—especially when leveraging automated rewriting systems that may introduce noise or semantic drift. While prior work has explored tagging mechanisms (e.g., Dialogue Act tagging, hierarchical rule tagging, or SRL-guided rewriting), these approaches primarily focus on improving the *generation* of rewritten utterances rather than actively *validating or correcting* them post-rewriting. My intuition is that instead of treating value tagging as a passive annotation tool, it can be reimagined as an active, differentiable semantic guardrail—a dynamic filter that both detects and rectifies inconsistencies by grounding utterance semantics in structured value spaces (e.g., slot-value pairs common in task-oriented dialogues). This builds upon the insight from Paper 2 that taggers benefit from constrained copying, and from Paper 3 that linguistic structure improves rewriting accuracy, but goes further by introducing a feedback loop where a value tagger supervises the rewriting process through zero-shot generalization across domains. Unlike consistency regularization in Paper 1—which uses masking for domain adaptation—my idea leverages masked value prediction not just for augmentation, but as a supervision signal for error correction. The novelty lies in using the tagger not only to *assess* correctness but to *guide iterative refinement* of noisy rewrites via differentiable relaxation of discrete tags (e.g., using soft label distributions), enabling end-to-end training without requiring explicit error annotations. This creates a self-correcting framework that generalizes to unseen domains by learning invariant value-grounding patterns.

